title: ChemInform Abstract: DIMERIZATION OF DIPHENYL(TRIFLUOROACETYL)PHOSPHINE OXIDE

items.abstract: <jats:p>The halogenated acylphosphines RC(O)PPh<jats:sub>2</jats:sub> (1a-f) [R = ClCH<jats:sub>2</jats:sub> (a), FCH<jats:sub>2</jats:sub> (b), F<jats:sub>2</jats:sub>CH (c), C<jats:sub>2</jats:sub>F<jats:sub>5</jats:sub> (d), C<jats:sub>3</jats:sub>F<jats:sub>7</jats:sub> (e), C<jats:sub>6</jats:sub>F<jats:sub>5</jats:sub> (f)], which can be oxidized by rigorously dried oxygen to the phos­phine oxides RC(O)P(O)Ph<jats:sub>2</jats:sub> (2a-f), are obtained by reaction of NaPPh<jats:sub>2</jats:sub> with the acyl chlorides RC(O)Cl. From 2a-f and stoichiometric amounts of water the alcohols RC[Ph<jats:sub>2</jats:sub>P(O)]<jats:sub>2</jats:sub>OH (3a-f) are formed. While 3c-f are isomerized into the phosphinates RC[Ph<jats:sub>2</jats:sub>P(O)][OP(O)Ph<jats:sub>2</jats:sub>]H (4c-f), the alcohols 3a, b are stable. The hydrolytic and thermal behavior of the phosphine oxides 2 and the alcohols 3 are discussed regarding the nature of the acyl residue. </jats:p>
